<h2>HVAC Systems in Ohio</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Ohio's humid continental climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, requiring equipment capable of handling both hot, humid summers with temperatures reaching into the 80s and 90s Fahrenheit, and cold winters with temperatures often dropping below freezing. The state experiences approximately 5,600 heating degree days and 800-1,000 cooling degree days annually, indicating that heating loads significantly exceed cooling loads throughout the year. This climate pattern makes dual-fuel heat pump systems particularly attractive, as they can provide efficient cooling during summer months and supplement heating during moderate winter conditions.</p>

<p>Humidity control is crucial in Ohio's climate, as summer humidity levels frequently exceed 70%. Modern HVAC systems must incorporate proper dehumidification capabilities to maintain indoor comfort and prevent moisture-related issues such as mold growth and poor indoor air quality. Variable-speed equipment excels in Ohio's climate because it can operate at lower capacities during mild weather while maintaining superior humidity control compared to single-stage systems.</p>

<p>Winter heating requirements in Ohio traditionally rely on natural gas furnaces, but the improving efficiency and cold-weather performance of modern heat pumps make them increasingly viable. Cold-climate heat pumps can now operate efficiently at temperatures as low as -10¬∞F, making them suitable for most of Ohio's winter conditions. When combined with solar panels, electric heat pumps can provide heating using clean, renewable energy rather than fossil fuels.</p>

