<h2>Ohio Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Ohio residents can take advantage of several incentive programs to reduce the cost of solar and HVAC installations. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, after which it steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total installed cost of the solar system, including equipment, installation labor, and permits. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds the homeowner's tax liability in the installation year.</p>

<p>Ohio offers a property tax exemption for solar energy systems, meaning the added value of a solar installation will not increase property tax assessments. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial solar installations and remains in effect for the life of the system. Additionally, Ohio does not charge sales tax on solar equipment, providing further cost savings of approximately 5.75% on the equipment portion of solar installations.</p>

<p>AEP Ohio offers various energy efficiency rebates through their gridSMART programs. These rebates can provide \$50-300 for qualifying high-efficiency HVAC equipment, smart thermostats, and heat pump water heaters. The utility also offers energy audits and weatherization rebates that can help homeowners identify and address energy efficiency opportunities. Some local municipalities and counties offer additional rebates or low-interest financing programs for energy efficiency improvements.</p>

<p>For HVAC systems, federal tax credits are available for qualifying high-efficiency equipment. Heat pumps with HSPF2 ratings of 8.5 or higher and SEER2 ratings of 15 or higher qualify for a \$2,000 federal tax credit. Central air conditioning systems with SEER2 ratings of 16 or higher qualify for \$300 credits. Geothermal heat pump systems qualify for a 30% federal tax credit similar to solar installations, making them particularly attractive for Ohio homeowners.</p>

